To compare the HER activity of considered materials, we generated volcanic curves depicting the variations in Gibbs free energy (ΔGH) and exchange current density (i0) for TCDs, as illustrated in Fig. 7
                        . The value of exchange current is calculated using the Eq. (10). Among the investigated species, N-doped TCD displayed superior catalytic activity, characterized by the lowest current density and Gibbs free energy values. Comparative analysis revealed that N-doped TCD (−0.19 eV), TCD (−0.26 eV) and B- doped TCD (−0.51 eV) exhibited HER catalytic potential when compared to various benchmark materials, including Co@C12 (−0.23 eV), Fe@C20 (−0.20 eV), Cu@C24 (−0.20 eV), V@C24 (−0.18 eV), Zn@C60 (−0.28 eV), V@C60 (0.12 eV), FeMo@C24 (0.12 eV), Ni@Al6N6 (0.18 eV), Co@B12P12 (−0.20 eV). This comparative analysis underscores the superior HER catalytic potential of N-doped TCD, pristine TCD and B-doped TCD, positioning them as promising candidates for HER applications (Table 4
                        ).
